:: TheKind.Session2.Offer_Reading_Silence
You don't say anything. You just sit with the cards in front of you and let the reading nook do what it does.

Dev looks at the table. At the deck. At the colored lamplight on the worn hardwood. The silence stretches, but it doesn't break — it *holds.* The way a rest in music holds, the way a proof holds, the way a good store holds the people who wander into it.

"Are those tarot cards?"

"Yeah."

"Do you... do you do readings?"

"If you want."

He sits with it. The CS major in him wants to dismiss it. The part of him that grew up watching his grandmother light incense and say prayers in a language he only half-understands — the part that knows there are ways of knowing that don't compile — that part is curious.

"I don't know what I want," he says. "I just know that nothing I've been doing is working."

"That's a good place to start."

