:: TheKind.Session2.CardDraw
@py:
# Card pools for each position
# Reversal chance: 0.25 (slightly higher than S1 — Dev's situation is fraught)
position_1_deck = Deck(cards=["Ten of Wands", "The Emperor", "Knight of Pentacles"], reversals=[0.25, 0.25, 0.25])
position_2_deck = Deck(cards=["The Tower", "Eight of Swords", "Two of Swords"], reversals=[0.25, 0.25, 0.25])
position_3_deck = Deck(cards=["The Magician", "Ace of Wands", "Page of Cups"], reversals=[0.25, 0.25, 0.25])

reading = Reading(spread_id="solid-ground", decks=[
    position_1_deck,
    position_2_deck,
    position_3_deck
])

cards = reading.draw_cards()
@endpy

@render render_reading(reading=reading)

You lay down three cards in a line. Left to right. The colored lamplight catches each one as it lands on the worn hardwood.

**Position 1 (What You're Carrying):** {cards[0].name}{cards[0].reversed ?  — Reversed | }
**Position 2 (What's Actually In The Way):** {cards[1].name}{cards[1].reversed ?  — Reversed | }
**Position 3 (What Strength You Don't See Yet):** {cards[2].name}{cards[2].reversed ?  — Reversed | }

Dev studies them the way he'd study code — looking for structure, for logic, for the thing that makes the whole system cohere. His glasses reflect the lamplight. His hands are in his lap, not clasped like Ellen's were — fisted. The knuckles of someone who has been gripping something too hard for too long.

"I don't know what any of these mean," he says.

"That's fine. That's my job."

He almost smiles. "Okay. Show me."

