"Ten of Wands reversed often means a burden being released — or needing to be."

You look at Dev. At the heaviness in his frame that isn't just the rain.

"You've been carrying this alone. Not just the math. The whole thing. Being the first one in your family to do this, with nobody ahead of you on the trail to say 'here's where it gets steep, here's where you need to rest.'"

Dev goes still. The stillness of someone who just heard their own story told back to them by a stranger.

"My roommate's dad is an engineer," Dev says. "He calls his dad when he's stuck on problem sets. Just... calls him. And his dad helps. Like it's nothing."

He stares at the card.

"I didn't even know that was a thing people did."

From the back of the store, the sound of Mal's footsteps stopping. They've been moving through the stacks — you can track Mal by sound the way you track weather, by shifts in pressure — and now they've stopped. They heard that. You know they heard that because three years ago, Mal was a junior ML engineer at a startup in Portland, debugging a neural architecture at 2am because they were the only person on the team without a Stanford pedigree and they thought asking for help meant admitting they didn't belong. They quit six months later. Not because the work was too hard — because the loneliness of pretending it wasn't hard was worse than the work itself.

