# --- THE EMPEROR ---

:: TheKind.Session2.P1_Emperor
@if cards[0].reversed:
    The Emperor — reversed. A throne, a crown, a figure of authority and order — but inverted. Structure that's become rigid. Authority that's become oppressive. Or: a father figure whose expectations have calcified into law.

    Dev studies it with the careful attention of someone trained to read systems. "That's a king?"

    "An emperor. Structure, authority, order. The person who builds the system everyone else operates in. Reversed means the system itself might be the problem."

    Scout looks at the card and then at Dev and something connects behind his eyes — the particular look Scout gets when two things that seem unrelated suddenly share a key signature. He grew up in a house split between two cultural pressures: his mom's family in Krakow who expected him to study engineering, and his dad's family in Nagoya who expected him to study medicine. He studied neither. He works in a record store. He hasn't called his grandparents in four months.

    Delphi, from behind the counter, pours tea. Not for herself. For the conversation. She's feeding the room the way you feed a fire — small additions, steady heat.

    + ["Reversed Emperor is about a structure that's supposed to support you but instead is crushing you. Not a person — a *system.* The system that said 'you're smart, you'll figure it out' and then gave you no tools and no roadmap and called it a meritocracy. The system that confused your ability to survive with your ability to thrive, and never checked the difference."] -> TheKind.Session2.P1_Emperor_R_Empathic
    + ["This reversal points to authority that's failed its responsibility. Somewhere along the line, a structure that was supposed to prepare you — a school, a department, a curriculum — skipped a step. The card isn't blaming you. It's blaming the architecture."] -> TheKind.Session2.P1_Emperor_R_Reframing
    + ["Reversed Emperor can mean issues with a father figure or authority. Is your relationship with your parents putting pressure on your academics?"] -> TheKind.Session2.P1_Emperor_R_Clinical
    + ["This reversed card suggests structural problems. Something in the system isn't working."] -> TheKind.Session2.P1_Emperor_R_Vague
@else:
    The Emperor. A figure on a throne, armored, commanding. Structure. Authority. The person who built the rules and expects them followed. Order as both foundation and cage.

    Dev's expression shifts when he sees it. Not recognition — resonance. Something about the rigidity of the figure, the weight of the throne, the armor that's both protection and imprisonment.

    "That's a lot of... structure," Dev says.

    "It is."

    From behind the vinyl bins, Scout makes a face. Scout has a complicated relationship with authority — his own staff picks shelf is organized by emotional logic that defies every filing convention ever invented, and he once got into a twenty-minute debate with a customer about whether Radiohead's *Kid A* belonged in the "rock" section or the "what happened to rock" section. The Emperor is everything Scout isn't, and he knows it.

    Mal, however. Mal looks at the card with something like recognition. Mal *is* structure. Mal is the composition notebooks, the precise cataloging, the system that makes the impossible shelves navigable. But Mal chose their own structure. They didn't inherit it. That's the difference.

    + ["The Emperor represents the weight of expectations — not just yours, but the structure you grew up inside. Be the smart kid. Get the grades. Go to college. It's not that these were wrong — they got you here. But 'here' is a place where the same rules don't work anymore, and the Emperor doesn't know how to say 'I don't know what comes next.'"] -> TheKind.Session2.P1_Emperor_U_Empathic
    + ["This card is about systems of order. You've been operating inside a system your whole life — the system of 'work hard, be smart, figure it out.' And it's a good system. It got you through calc 1, 2, 3. It got you into Carruth. But real analysis isn't inside that system. It requires a different kind of thinking, and nobody told you the rules changed."] -> TheKind.Session2.P1_Emperor_U_Reframing
    + ["The Emperor represents structure and authority. Do you feel like academic expectations are weighing on you?"] -> TheKind.Session2.P1_Emperor_U_Practical
    + ["Strong card. Represents authority and structure in your life."] -> TheKind.Session2.P1_Emperor_U_Vague
@endif

# Emperor — Upright interpretations

:: TheKind.Session2.P1_Emperor_U_Empathic
"The Emperor represents the weight of expectations — not just yours, but the structure you grew up inside."

Dev listens. The CS-major part of him is parsing; the rest of him is feeling.

"Be the smart kid. Get the grades. Go to college. These aren't wrong — they got you *here.* But 'here' is a place where the same rules don't work anymore, and the Emperor doesn't know how to say 'I don't know what comes next.'"

Dev's voice goes quiet. "My dad has a photo of me at the restaurant. Behind the register. Me at my high school graduation. He laminated it."

He stares at the card.

"He tells every customer. 'My son goes to Carruth. Computer science AND mathematics.' Both. He always says both."

The rain on the roof. The colored lamplight. Dev, in the chair, looking at a card that looks like a throne and seeing a laminated photo behind a restaurant register.

"I can't be the person who only does one."

