# --- THE TOWER ---

:: TheKind.Session2.P2_Tower
@if cards[1].reversed:
    The Tower — reversed. A crumbling structure, lightning, figures falling — but upside down, it's different. Not destruction from above. Slow erosion. A foundation that was never solid, finally revealing its cracks.

    Dev looks at the card for a long time. "That doesn't look great."

    "It's not as bad as it looks. Reversed, it's less 'explosion' and more 'the thing you thought was solid turns out to have been cracking for a while.'"

    Scout shifts behind the vinyl bins. The Tower makes him uncomfortable — it's the *Kid A* of the tarot, the card that says everything you thought you knew is wrong and you have to rebuild from silence. He reaches for the headphones around his neck like a talisman.

    + ["The Tower reversed, in this position, is actually precise: the thing that's in your way is a foundation that was never properly laid. Not by you — by the system. The educational structure that got you from third grade to a college junior was built on computation and repetition, and it looks solid, and it *is* solid for everything it was designed for. But it was never designed for this. The cracks aren't new. They've been there since someone decided a kid who could compute didn't also need to learn to prove."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_Tower_R_Empathic
    + ["Reversed Tower means the collapse is internal, not dramatic. The building didn't explode — it's settling. And when you look at why, you find that one of the load-bearing walls was never actually built. That's not your fault. You can't build a wall you didn't know was supposed to be there."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_Tower_R_Reframing
    + ["Reversed Tower means personal upheaval. You're going through a difficult transition period."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_Tower_R_Practical
    + ["This reversed card means the worst is over. The crisis is passing."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_Tower_R_Vague
@else:
    The Tower. Lightning splitting a tower in half. Figures falling. Flames. The most feared card in the deck — and in the "What's Actually In The Way" position, the most honest.

    Dev: "That's..." He swallows. "That's a building on fire."

    "It's a *revelation.* The Tower doesn't destroy — it reveals what was already unstable. The lightning doesn't create the cracks. It illuminates them."

    The effect on the room is immediate. Scout takes a half-step back. Delphi leans forward. From the stacks, you hear Mal's footsteps stop completely — the particular silence of someone who just recognized the card before you said it.

    + ["The Tower in this position tells me the obstacle isn't your intelligence, your work ethic, or your dedication. The obstacle is a *revelation* you haven't had yet — or maybe one you've been having for three weeks and refusing to accept: the foundation you've been building on has a gap in it. Not because you built it wrong. Because someone gave you the wrong blueprints."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_Tower_U_Empathic
    + ["Everyone's afraid of the Tower. But here's the secret: the Tower only destroys things that were built wrong. The things that were built right? They survive. The lightning is diagnostic. It's a stress test. And what it's telling you is that one specific part of your preparation — not your ability, not your work ethic, one specific structural element — can't bear the load it's being asked to carry. Identify the weak point and reinforce it, and the rest of the building stands."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_Tower_U_Poetic
    + ["The Tower means something needs to break down before it can be rebuilt properly. Your current approach to the material isn't working and needs to change."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_Tower_U_Practical
    + ["Dramatic card. Major disruption ahead. Things may get worse before they get better."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_Tower_U_Vague
@endif

# Tower — Upright interpretations

:: TheKind.Session2.P2_Tower_U_Empathic
"The Tower in this position tells me the obstacle isn't your intelligence, your work ethic, or your dedication."

Dev tenses. Bracing.

"The obstacle is a *revelation* you haven't had yet — or maybe one you've been having for three weeks and refusing to accept."

"What revelation?"

"That the foundation you've been building on has a gap in it. Not because you built it wrong. Because someone gave you the wrong blueprints."

The word *blueprints* does something. Dev is a CS major — he thinks in architecture, in systems, in specifications. A wrong blueprint isn't a personal failure. It's an engineering problem. And engineering problems have solutions.

"So the gap is—"

"Proof-writing. Mathematical reasoning. The bridge between 'I can compute the answer' and 'I can explain *why* the answer is true.' It's a learnable skill, Dev. It's not magic. It's not talent. It's a course you never took because nobody told you it existed."

Something breaks. Not dramatically — quietly, like ice cracking on a river in early spring. The first fracture that means the thaw is coming.

"A course." His voice is very small. "There was a *course.*"

Delphi, from behind the counter: "MATH 201. Introduction to Mathematical Reasoning. Kessler doesn't list it as a prerequisite. She should."

