:: TheKind.Session2.P2_Tower_U_Poetic
"Everyone's afraid of the Tower. But here's the secret."

Dev braces. The way you brace for bad news. The way he's been bracing for three weeks.

"The Tower only destroys things that were built wrong. The things that were built right? They survive."

His jaw unclenches. One degree.

"The lightning is diagnostic. It's a stress test. And what it's telling you is that one specific part of your preparation — not your ability, not your work ethic, one specific structural element — can't bear the load it's being asked to carry."

You hold his gaze.

"Identify the weak point and reinforce it, and the rest of the building stands."

"The weak point is proofs." Dev says it himself this time. Not as a confession — as a diagnosis. The engineer in him taking over, locating the bug. "I can do everything else. I understand the *concepts*. When Kessler explains a theorem on the board, I get it. I can see why it's true. But when I sit down to write the proof—"

"You don't have the language."

"I don't have the *language.*" He says it with relief. With the specific relief of a person who just found the name for the thing that's been nameless and terrifying for weeks. It's not that he can't think. It's that nobody taught him the grammar.

From somewhere in the stacks, Mal: "That's exactly what it is. Proof-writing is a language. Rudin assumes you're fluent."

