# Tower — Reversed interpretations

:: TheKind.Session2.P2_Tower_R_Empathic
"The Tower reversed, in this position, is actually precise."

Dev watches you.

"The thing that's in your way is a foundation that was never properly laid. Not by you — by the system. The educational structure that got you from third grade to a college junior was built on computation and repetition, and it looks solid, and it *is* solid for everything it was designed for."

You touch the card.

"But it was never designed for this. The cracks aren't new. They've been there since someone decided a kid who could compute didn't also need to learn to prove."

Dev is quiet for a long time. The rain fills the silence.

"In second grade," he says, "I taught myself multiplication from a library book because the teacher said we wouldn't learn it until third grade and I wanted to know now. My mom was so proud. She told everyone at the restaurant."

He stares at the card.

"I've been teaching myself everything since second grade. And this is the first time it's not working."

The store creaks. Not the creak of settling — the creak of a building that's paying attention. The pressed tin ceiling seems to lower slightly, not oppressive, protective. The way a parent bends down to hear a child better.

