"Reversed Tower means the collapse is internal, not dramatic. The building didn't explode — it's settling. And when you look at why, you find that one of the load-bearing walls was never actually built."

Dev's engineering brain engages. "A missing load-bearing wall."

"That's not your fault. You can't build a wall you didn't know was supposed to be there."

He sits with that. The metaphor is precise enough for him to work with — to turn over, to inspect, to debug.

"So the wall is..."

"Proof technique. Mathematical reasoning. The formal grammar of abstract mathematics. It's usually taught as a bridge course between calculus and analysis. Did you take one?"

Dev shakes his head slowly. "Nobody said I needed to."

"Nobody said you needed to."

