# --- EIGHT OF SWORDS ---

:: TheKind.Session2.P2_EightSwords
@if cards[1].reversed:
    The Eight of Swords — reversed. A blindfolded figure surrounded by swords, bound — but upside down, the blindfold is slipping. The bonds are loosening. The prison was always partially self-constructed.

    Dev studies it. "That person is tied up."

    "They think they are. Look closer — the bindings are loose. The swords aren't touching them. The cage is mostly perception."

    From behind the vinyl bins, Scout makes a sound. He knows this card. He *is* this card, some days — the days when he can't recommend a record because every option feels wrong and the paralysis of caring too much looks like not caring at all. Delphi has a word for it: *overcuration.* The state of knowing so much about something that the knowledge becomes a trap instead of a tool.

    + ["Reversed, the blindfold is slipping. You're starting to see that the thing trapping you isn't real analysis — it's the story you're telling yourself *about* real analysis. 'I'm not smart enough.' 'Everyone else gets it.' 'I'm the only one struggling.' Those aren't facts. Those are the swords. And they're not touching you — you just can't see past them."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_EightSwords_R_Empathic
    + ["This reversal means the prison is opening. The limiting belief — whatever it is — is starting to crack. Maybe you walked into this store thinking 'I'm not cut out for this.' And the fact that you sat down for this reading means part of you already knows that's not true."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_EightSwords_R_Reframing
    + ["Eight of Swords reversed means you're starting to see through your limitations. That's positive progress."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_EightSwords_R_Practical
    + ["Good news — this reversed card means liberation from restriction. You'll break free soon."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_EightSwords_R_Vague
@else:
    The Eight of Swords. A blindfolded figure, bound, surrounded by eight swords planted in the ground. Trapped — but the trap is more psychological than physical. The bindings are loose. The swords don't actually touch them. The prison is built from belief.

    Dev looks at the image and his expression goes very still. The stillness of recognition.

    "They can't move," he says. Quiet.

    "They *think* they can't move. Look at the bindings. They're loose. Look at the swords — there's a gap. The figure could walk out. But they can't see it because of the blindfold."

    Scout is watching Dev now with the focus he usually reserves for live performances — the moments when an artist is doing something vulnerable and real and you can't look away because looking away would be a kind of betrayal.

    Mal has come to the edge of the aisle. Not into the reading nook — they respect the space — but close enough to hear. Their expression is the one you've seen twice before: the one that means the reading just touched something in them personally that they didn't expect and they're choosing to stay instead of retreat.

    Delphi sets both palms on the counter. Flat. The posture of someone about to deliver a truth.

    + ["The swords are the stories you tell yourself about who you are and what you're capable of. 'I'm the first one in my family to go to college, so if I fail it means the whole bet was wrong.' 'Everyone else in the class is smarter than me.' 'Asking for help means admitting I don't belong here.' Those are the swords, Dev. And they're not even pointed at you. You pointed them at yourself."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_EightSwords_U_Empathic
    + ["This card is about perceived limitations versus real ones. Your real limitation is a missing bridge course. Your *perceived* limitation is 'I'm not smart enough for abstract math.' The gap between those two things — between the structural problem and the story you've built around it — that gap is what's actually in the way. Not the math. The *narrative.*"] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_EightSwords_U_Reframing
    + ["Eight of Swords means feeling trapped. You're stuck in a situation that feels worse than it actually is."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_EightSwords_U_Practical
    + ["This card shows you feel restricted. Try to see past your current limitations."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_EightSwords_U_Vague
@endif

# Eight of Swords — Upright interpretations

:: TheKind.Session2.P2_EightSwords_U_Empathic
"The swords are the stories you tell yourself about who you are and what you're capable of."

Dev's hands go back to fists. You're getting close.

"'I'm the first one in my family to go to college, so if I fail it means the whole bet was wrong.'"

His breath catches.

"'Everyone else in the class is smarter than me.'"

"They're not—"

"'Asking for help means admitting I don't belong here.'"

Dev stops. The protest dies. Because that one — that last one — is the sword that's actually doing the damage.

"I went to office hours once," he says. Very quiet. The kind of quiet that costs something. "First week. Professor Kessler. I asked about a proof technique in the homework and she said—"

He stops. Swallows.

"She said, 'This is covered in the prerequisite material. You should review your notes from your transition course.'"

The reading nook is absolutely still.

"I didn't have notes from a transition course. I didn't have a transition course. I said 'okay' and I left and I never went back to office hours."

Behind the counter, Delphi makes a sound. Not loud. The sound of someone who hears this every fall and is furious every fall and has been furious for longer than Dev has been alive.

"That's not a sword you pointed at yourself," you say. "That one came from outside."

"It doesn't matter where it came from. It's still there."

"Then let's look at it. That's what the next card is for."

