# --- TWO OF SWORDS ---

:: TheKind.Session2.P2_TwoSwords
@if cards[1].reversed:
    The Two of Swords — reversed. A blindfolded figure holding two crossed swords over their heart. Balanced, rigid, refusing to choose. But reversed — the swords dropping, the refusal crumbling. A decision being forced.

    Dev studies it. "Another blindfold."

    "Different blindfold. The Eight of Swords is trapped. The Two of Swords is *choosing* not to see. There's something you already know that you're refusing to look at."

    Delphi shifts behind the counter. The particular shift of someone who knows what the something is and is waiting for the reading to arrive there.

    + ["Reversed, the swords are dropping. The thing you've been refusing to confront — the fact that you need *help*, real help, structural help, not just 'try harder' help — is becoming impossible to avoid. You walked into this store looking for a textbook. You know that's not what you need. You've known for weeks. The two swords were keeping the knowledge at bay and they're falling now."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_TwoSwords_R_Empathic
    + ["This reversal means a difficult truth is surfacing. The obstacle isn't your ability — it's your refusal to acknowledge the gap. Not out of pride. Out of fear. Because if the gap is real, then the story you've been telling yourself — 'I can figure out anything alone' — has an exception. And the exception terrifies you."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_TwoSwords_R_Reframing
    + ["Two of Swords reversed means a decision you've been avoiding is being forced. What have you been putting off?"] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_TwoSwords_R_Practical
    + ["This reversed card means indecision is resolving. You'll find clarity soon."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_TwoSwords_R_Vague
@else:
    The Two of Swords. A blindfolded figure holding two swords crossed over their chest. Water behind them. A choice they refuse to make, held in painful balance by sheer force of will.

    Dev looks at it. "What's with the blindfold? Two blindfold cards?"

    "Different kind. This one is voluntary. You're *choosing* not to see something."

    His jaw sets. "I'm not choosing anything. I'm trying to pass a class."

    "You're trying to pass a class by doing the same thing that isn't working, harder and more. That's a choice. The choice not to look at the real problem."

    Scout winces from behind the bins. Not because you're wrong — because he recognizes the move. Scout has a shelf in the back of the store labeled "Albums I Play When I'm Avoiding Something" and it has forty entries and he knows every one by heart. Avoidance has its own discography.

    Mal's pen has stopped entirely. They've set the composition notebook down on a shelf. That never happens. The notebook is an extension of Mal the way the turntable is an extension of Scout. Setting it down means full attention. Means this matters in a way the notebook can't catalog.

    + ["The two swords are the two things you're balancing: 'I can do this alone' and 'I'm drowning.' You can't hold both. They're contradictory and the effort of holding them crossed over your heart is exhausting. The obstacle isn't real analysis. It's the refusal to choose between those two truths — to either admit you need help or accept that you're going to drown."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_TwoSwords_U_Empathic
    + ["There's a concept in CS called a deadlock — two processes each waiting for the other to release a resource. That's this card. Part of you knows you need a different approach. Part of you is afraid that admitting that means everything before was wrong. Neither part will yield. So you're frozen. The blindfold isn't ignorance — it's a deadlock."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_TwoSwords_U_Reframing
    + ["Two of Swords means avoidance. There's a truth you're not confronting about your situation."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_TwoSwords_U_Practical
    + ["This card means you need to make a decision. Stop being indecisive."] -> TheKind.Session2.P2_TwoSwords_U_Vague
@endif

# Two of Swords — Upright interpretations

:: TheKind.Session2.P2_TwoSwords_U_Empathic
"The two swords are the two things you're balancing: 'I can do this alone' and 'I'm drowning.' You can't hold both."

Dev's hands grip the edge of the table.

"They're contradictory and the effort of holding them crossed over your heart is exhausting."

"I'm not—"

"The obstacle isn't real analysis. It's the refusal to choose between those two truths — to either admit you need help or accept that you're going to drown."

The word *drown* hits. Dev's eyes go bright behind the wire-rimmed glasses. Not tears — the precursor. The pressure of something being named that's been nameless.

"I've been going to the library every night," he says. "Every night. 7pm to midnight. Five hours of staring at Rudin. Five hours of reading the same proof over and over and not—" His voice breaks. Just slightly. A hairline crack. "I rewrite my notes. I watch YouTube. I go to the optional review sessions and I sit in the back and I *still* don't get it and nobody notices because I'm quiet about it because that's what I do. I'm quiet about it."

Behind the counter, Delphi picks up the mug she poured for Dev — the one he took without thinking, the one that's been cooling in his hands — and without saying a word, she comes around the counter and refills it. Pours from the kettle. Slides it back. Eye contact. Brief. A look that says: *I hear you. You're not invisible. Not here.*

