"Not out of pride. Out of fear. Because if the gap is real, then the story you've been telling yourself — 'I can figure out anything alone' — has an exception."

"And the exception terrifies you."

Dev goes very still. Then, quietly: "If I can't figure this out alone... then maybe all the other times I figured things out alone were just luck. Maybe I was never actually smart. Maybe the tests were just easy and the teachers were just nice and—"

"Stop." Delphi's voice. Not harsh. Sharp. "That's impostor syndrome talking. And it's wrong. You're not lucky. You're talented and underprepared. Those are different things."

The silence after is heavy and warm, like the store itself pressing in, wrapping around Dev the way rain wraps around Rewind.

