# --- THE MAGICIAN ---

:: TheKind.Session2.P3_Magician
@if cards[2].reversed:
    The Magician — reversed. A figure at a table with all four elemental tools — wand, cup, sword, pentacle — but inverted. The tools are there but the connection to them is blocked. Power untapped. Potential unrecognized.

    Dev looks at the image. "What are all those things on the table?"

    "Everything you need. The Magician has every tool. Reversed means you haven't recognized that yet."

    Scout has gone very quiet. The Magician reversed is the card he'd draw for himself on the bad days — the days when he knows every album in the store but can't find the one a customer needs, when the knowledge feels like clutter instead of capability. He gets it.

    + ["Every tool you need is already on the table. Reversed Magician doesn't mean the tools are missing — it means you're looking right at them and not seeing them. Your computational skills, your CS intuition, your ability to break complex systems into components — that's not separate from mathematical thinking. That IS mathematical thinking. You've been doing proofs your whole coding life. You just didn't know that's what they were called."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_Magician_R_Empathic
    + ["The Magician reversed is untapped potential. You already think in systems. You already debug. You already trace logical paths through complex architectures. Real analysis is the same skill wearing different clothes. The obstacle isn't that you can't think abstractly — you think abstractly every time you write code. The obstacle is that nobody ever told you the thinking you're already doing has a name in mathematics."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_Magician_R_Reframing
    + ["Reversed Magician suggests you have untapped potential. You're more capable than you think."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_Magician_R_Practical
    + ["Good card. You have hidden strengths that will emerge."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_Magician_R_Vague
@else:
    The Magician. A figure at a table with every tool — wand, cup, sword, pentacle. One hand pointing to the sky, the other to the earth. Above, the infinity symbol. The card of someone who has *everything they need* and knows how to use it.

    Dev stares at it. "That looks... powerful."

    "It is. The Magician is the card that says you already have every tool. You just haven't connected them yet."

    From behind the bins, Scout straightens up. The Magician is his favorite card — the card of the person who takes disparate inputs and synthesizes them into something new. It's what Scout does every time he connects Joni Mitchell to Frank Ocean, every time he files Deafheaven next to Björk. Synthesis. The Magician's gift.

    Mal looks at the card and then at Dev and the expression on their face changes. It goes from clinical to warm. Because The Magician, for Mal, is the card that says: *you left the algorithm for a reason. The reason was this. The reason was knowing that a human being can do what no machine can — take everything they know and make something new.*

    Delphi just nods. She already knew.

    + ["Look at what you bring to this table. Not the math table — *this* table. You write code. You build systems. You take complex specifications and translate them into working architectures. Dev — that's what a proof IS. A proof is a logical architecture that starts from axioms and builds, step by step, to a conclusion. You've been writing proofs in Python for two years. The only thing you're missing is the *notation.*"] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_Magician_U_Empathic
    + ["The Magician has four tools and infinite potential. You have computation, you have logic, you have pattern recognition, and you have the most underrated tool of all — you have the ability to sit with something you don't understand for hours without giving up. Do you know how rare that is? Most people quit. You went to the library every night for three weeks and you're still here. The Magician doesn't give up. The Magician finds the connection."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_Magician_U_Poetic
    + ["The Magician shows you have all the skills you need. You just need to apply them differently."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_Magician_U_Practical
    + ["Great card for your situation. Very positive."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_Magician_U_Vague
@endif

# Magician — Upright interpretations

:: TheKind.Session2.P3_Magician_U_Empathic
"Look at what you bring to this table. Not the math table — *this* table."

Dev listens. The skepticism is still there, but underneath it, something is hoping.

"You write code. You build systems. You take complex specifications and translate them into working architectures."

He nods. Carefully.

"Dev — that's what a proof *is.* A proof is a logical architecture that starts from axioms and builds, step by step, to a conclusion. You've been writing proofs in Python for two years. The only thing you're missing is the *notation.*"

Something happens behind his eyes. The click. The compile. The moment when code that's been throwing errors suddenly runs and the output makes sense.

"Functions," he says. Slowly. "Proofs are like functions. You declare your inputs — the axioms. You apply operations — the logical steps. And the return value is the conclusion."

From the stacks, Mal: "Yes." One word. But the way Mal says it — with the weight of someone who crossed the same bridge from a different direction — makes it land like a theorem.

Dev's hands open. Palms up on the table. Like he's holding something he just received.

"I've been trying to learn a new language. But it's not a new language. It's a different *syntax* for the same language."

"That's the Magician. Everything you need is already on the table."

