"The Magician has four tools and infinite potential. You have computation, you have logic, you have pattern recognition, and you have the most underrated tool of all."

Dev waits.

"You have the ability to sit with something you don't understand for hours without giving up. Do you know how rare that is?"

He blinks. He's never thought of persistence as a *tool.* It's just... what he does. What the kid from Mehta's Kitchen does. You sit at the table and you work because the alternative is not working and that's not an option.

"Most people quit. You went to the library every night for three weeks and you're still here. In a store. In the rain. At nine o'clock on a Tuesday. Looking for a textbook."

"That's not a skill. That's just... not giving up."

"Dev. *Not giving up* is the Magician's first and greatest tool. Everything else is technique. Technique can be taught. The thing that can't be taught — the thing the card is showing me — is the person who walks through the rain to a store they've never been in because Thursday is coming and they don't quit."

Scout is absolutely going to cry. He's doing the thing where he presses his lips together very hard and looks at the ceiling.

