# Magician — Reversed interpretations

:: TheKind.Session2.P3_Magician_R_Empathic
"Every tool you need is already on the table."

Dev looks at you.

"Reversed Magician doesn't mean the tools are missing — it means you're looking right at them and not seeing them. Your computational skills, your CS intuition, your ability to break complex systems into components — that's not separate from mathematical thinking."

You lean forward.

"That IS mathematical thinking. You've been doing proofs your whole coding life. You just didn't know that's what they were called."

Dev processes this. You can almost see the threads connecting — the if-then logic of code, the if-then logic of proofs. The way a function takes defined inputs and produces guaranteed outputs. The way a proof takes axioms and produces theorems. The *same architecture, different syntax.*

"When I write a function," he says slowly, "I start with the type signature. What goes in, what comes out. And then I build the implementation step by step, making sure each step follows from the last."

"That's a proof."

"...that's a proof."

The reversal flips. The tools on the Magician's table click into focus. The strength Dev didn't see was the strength he's been using every day in a different context.

