# --- PAGE OF CUPS ---

:: TheKind.Session2.P3_PageCups
@if cards[2].reversed:
    The Page of Cups — reversed. A young figure holding a cup from which a fish emerges — whimsical, emotional, surprising. But reversed, the emotional openness is blocked. The willingness to be surprised, to be a beginner, to feel — that's what's been shut down.

    + ["Reversed Page of Cups is the strength you've *suppressed.* The ability to be a beginner. To not know. To say 'I don't understand this' without hearing it as 'I'm not good enough.' You've been the expert your whole life — the kid who knew the answers, the one the family counted on. Being a beginner again feels like failure. But it's not. It's the prerequisite for learning."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_PageCups_R_Empathic
    + ["This reversal shows emotional vulnerability being blocked. The Page of Cups is about beginner's mind — the openness of someone who doesn't know and isn't ashamed of not knowing. You've forgotten how to not know. Or rather, you've forgotten that not knowing is where all learning starts."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_PageCups_R_Reframing
    + ["Reversed Page of Cups suggests blocked emotions. Allow yourself to feel what you're going through."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_PageCups_R_Practical
    + ["You're blocking your emotional side. Try to be more open."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_PageCups_R_Vague
@else:
    The Page of Cups. A young figure looking at a cup with wonder — a fish leaping from it, unexpected, magical. The card of emotional openness. Beginner's mind. The willingness to be surprised.

    Dev looks at it. The fish makes him almost-smile.

    "There's a fish in the cup."

    "There's always a fish in the cup. That's the Page's gift — they look at ordinary things and find something extraordinary."

    Scout perks up. The Page of Cups is the card Scout would tattoo on his arm if Delphi didn't keep talking him out of it. It's the card of the person who puts on a record they've never heard and is *ready* to be changed by it. Open. Undefended. Curious.

    Delphi watches Dev's face. The almost-smile. The guard that dropped for a moment when the fish surprised him. *There,* her expression says. *That's the crack.*

    Mal has set down the composition notebook entirely. They're just standing at the edge of the aisle, arms crossed, watching the reading the way you'd watch a proof unfold — patiently, attentively, knowing it's going somewhere.

    + ["The Page of Cups is beginner's mind. The willingness to not know — to look at something and say 'I have no idea what this is' and feel *curious* instead of ashamed. That's the strength you've lost. Not because you're arrogant — because the system taught you that not knowing is failure. It's not. Not knowing is the beginning. Every mathematician who ever proved anything started by not knowing, and the great ones never forgot what that felt like."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_PageCups_U_Empathic
    + ["Do you know what the best programmers have in common? It's not talent. It's not experience. It's the ability to look at code they don't understand and think 'cool, let me figure this out' instead of 'I should already know this.' That's the Page of Cups. That's beginner's mind. And you've been so busy being the expert — the kid who always knows, the first-gen student who can't afford to not know — that you've forgotten the *joy* of not knowing. The joy of the fish in the cup."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_PageCups_U_Poetic
    + ["Page of Cups represents emotional openness and new perspectives. Try to approach the material with fresh eyes."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_PageCups_U_Practical
    + ["Nice card. Be open to new emotional experiences."] -> TheKind.Session2.P3_PageCups_U_Vague
@endif

# Page of Cups — Upright interpretations

:: TheKind.Session2.P3_PageCups_U_Empathic
"The Page of Cups is beginner's mind. The willingness to not know — to look at something and say 'I have no idea what this is' and feel *curious* instead of ashamed."

Dev's jaw works. Beginner's mind. The phrase lands with the specific weight of something he hasn't let himself be since he was old enough to be "the smart kid."

"That's the strength you've lost. Not because you're arrogant — because the system taught you that not knowing is failure."

"It *is* failure. If I don't know the material, I fail the exam—"

"Not knowing *yet* is different from not knowing *ever.* Every mathematician who ever proved anything started by not knowing. The great ones never forgot what that felt like."

Dev looks at the fish in the cup. At the wonder on the Page's face.

"My dadi," he says quietly. "When she was learning English. She was sixty. She'd sit at the restaurant counter with a children's book — *Goodnight Moon* — and she'd read it out loud. To nobody. To the restaurant. And she'd get the pronunciation wrong and she didn't care because she was *learning.*"

He stops. Takes off his glasses. Wipes them. Not because they're foggy.

"She never once seemed ashamed of not knowing."

"That's the Page of Cups."

"That's my dadi."

The store is very warm. The pressed tin ceiling seems to glow. Somewhere in the stacks, a book shifts on a shelf — not falling, adjusting. Making room.

