Dev, the CS major, leans forward. You're in his language now.

"It's not talent. It's not experience. It's the ability to look at code they don't understand and think 'cool, let me figure this out' instead of 'I should already know this.'"

His eyes widen. The recognition.

"That's the Page of Cups. That's beginner's mind. And you've been so busy being the expert — the kid who always knows, the first-gen student who can't afford to not know — that you've forgotten the *joy* of not knowing."

"The joy of—"

"The joy of the fish in the cup. The 'wait, what IS that?' feeling. You had it in linear algebra. You had it when you built your first neural net. You had it every time you encountered something beautiful and confusing and new."

Dev looks at the card. At the fish. At the Page's expression of open wonder.

"I used to love not knowing things," he says. "When did that change?"

"When the stakes got too high to enjoy it."

Scout, from behind the bins: "That's why you listen to music you've never heard. Because the not-knowing is the whole point. The first listen is the Page of Cups."

